      Basel endgame vs. green equity
   =20
 =20

The way that the US government encourages a lot of green energy projects is=
 by giving them tax credits. If you build a power plant that runs on certai=
n sorts of renewable resources, the Internal Revenue Service will give you =
some money=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0call it 0.3 cents per killowatt-hour
  [1]
=C2=A0=E2=80=94 for generating that power, which you can use to reduce your=
 taxes.=C2=A0
That is a reasonably safe stream of cash flows. Not totally safe =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0your plant could burn down, prices could collapse or costs could rise=
 so much that it is no longer economical to run it, the tax code could chan=
ge =E2=80=94=C2=A0but broadly speaking you can estimate how much power the =
plant will produce=C2=A0 per year and then multiply that by 0.3 cents to ge=
t a fairly predictable=C2=A0annual tax credit.=C2=A0
Finance being what it is, if you are building a green energy project, you w=
ill probably sell that tax credit. If your project will generate a quasi-gu=
aranteed stream of cash flows of $X per year for the next Y years, then you=
 can compute the present value of those cash flows=C2=A0and sell them, toda=
y, for that amount. This is good because you probably need a lot of cash, t=
oday,=C2=A0to build the green energy project.=C2=A0The government wants to =
encourage you to build the project, but the government doesn=E2=80=99t just=
 hand you the money to do it. Instead the government promises to pay you $X=
 per year if you succeed in building the project, and you need to take that=
 promise and exchange it for cash today in order to actually build the proj=
ect.
  [2]

The person giving you the cash =E2=80=94=C2=A0the person paying you money u=
p front today in exchange for a promise of the future tax credit =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0is probably a big US bank, for a few reasons. For one thing, banks ar=
e where the money is, and this sort of thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0providing finan=
cing today in exchange for a reasonably safe=C2=A0promise of future steady =
cash flows =E2=80=94=C2=A0is what banks do. And=C2=A0financial engineering=
=C2=A0=E2=80=94 looking at a provision of the tax code and being like =E2=
=80=9Cyeah we can wring some profits out of that" =E2=80=94=C2=A0is also wh=
at banks do.
Also, in the 2020s, a big part of what banks do is (1) promise to finance=
=C2=A0renewable energy projects and (2) deflect criticism for financing fos=
sil-fuel projects. (And, in the US,  vice versa.) So buying these tax credi=
ts =E2=80=94 paying=C2=A0the upfront costs of green energy projects in exch=
ange for the future green-energy tax credits =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a good way f=
or the banks to make money, do financial engineering, and show their shareh=
olders and critics that they are financing green energy projects.=C2=A0
I have suggested that the banks are=C2=A0buying=C2=A0the credits, and that =
the people building the projects =E2=80=94 the =E2=80=9Csponsors=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0are=C2=A0selling=C2=A0them, but that is not the correct term=
inology. You don=E2=80=99t go around selling tax credits, and your tax lawy=
ers will get mad if you say that. (Nothing here, of course, is tax advice.)=
 The tax credit is not your property; it is an artifact of US tax law. The =
only way for the bank to get the tax credit is by qualifying for the tax cr=
edit, and  the way to qualify for the tax credit is by=C2=A0owning=C2=A0the=
 renewable energy project.=C2=A0
And so the way this actually works is that the renewable energy project is =
set up as some sort of partnership or limited liability company or joint ve=
nture, and the sponsor is a co-owner and the bank is another co-owner. And =
the partnership agreement says that the sponsor gets most of the profits (a=
nd risk) from running the business and finding customers and selling electr=
icity at market rates and so forth, and the bank gets the tax credit. They =
are not=C2=A0exactly=C2=A0joint owners, but they are joint owners=C2=A0enou=
gh=C2=A0for the bank to take the tax credit. They have murmured the proper =
incantations to call themselves co-owners and take the tax credit.
The IRS actually gives instructions on what sorts of incantations you have =
to say. The IRS is in sort of a weird position here. On the one hand, it wa=
nts to prevent abusive tax shelters and generally uphold the aesthetic cohe=
rence of the tax code, so it does not want to allow people to just go aroun=
d selling tax credits.=C2=A0
On the other hand, the IRS=C2=A0does=C2=A0want to encourage these projects =
to get built, which does, practically, requiring selling the tax credit. So=
 it  provides=C2=A0guidance=C2=A0on, like, what is the least you can do to =
qualify. The bank does need to take some risk, to share in the downside of =
the project; the sponsor can=E2=80=99t guarantee the tax credits. But the u=
sual way it works, according to the  American Council on Renewable Energy, =
is that the bank and the sponsor form a project partnership, the bank =E2=
=80=9Cprovides between one-third to two-thirds of the total capital,=E2=80=
=9D and the bank gets back =E2=80=9C99% of the tax attributes and a minorit=
y share of the cash, typically between 5% and 30%,=E2=80=9D for a while. Th=
is ends either when the bank reaches its target return (a =E2=80=9Cyield-ba=
sed flip=E2=80=9D) or after an agreed amount of time (a =E2=80=9Ctime-based=
 flip=E2=80=9D), after which the bank=E2=80=99s share of the tax credit goe=
s down (=E2=80=9Cusually to about 5%=E2=80=9D) and the sponsor can buy it o=
ut.
This is called =E2=80=9Ctax equity financing,=E2=80=9D because for tax-law-=
incantation purposes, the bank is an=C2=A0equity owner=C2=A0of the partners=
hip. But for practical purposes, people kind of think of it as=C2=A0debt=C2=
=A0financing, because the bank is=C2=A0providing upfront money in exchange =
for a reasonably certain, reasonably fixed, reasonably time-limited=C2=A0re=
turn. It does not really share in the upside and the downside of the projec=
t; it=E2=80=99s just putting up money to buy the tax credit.
That=E2=80=99s how financial engineering works: You build a thing that look=
s like debt to the sponsor, and that looks like debt to the bank (so it=E2=
=80=99s happy to =E2=80=9Clend=E2=80=9D the money), but that looks like equ=
ity to the IRS (so the bank can get the tax credit).
But nothing is that simple. Banks are doing a lot of financial engineering =
behind the scenes, too, particularly for their capital requirements. A bank=
 funds itself with a mix of cheap debt (deposits, etc.) and expensive capit=
al (shareholder equity), and capital regulation determines how much capital=
 it needs. The capital regulation is focused largely on the=C2=A0riskiness=
=C2=A0of the bank=E2=80=99s assets: A bank that holds mostly Treasury bills=
 needs very little capital, while a bank that holds mostly Bitcoin needs a =
ton. This is called =E2=80=9Crisk-based capital,=E2=80=9D and it is express=
ed in terms of =E2=80=9Crisk weights=E2=80=9D: Treasury bills have a risk w=
eight of 0%, because they are safe, while   Bitcoin has a risk weight of 1,=
250%, because it is risky. Standard corporate loans usually have a risk wei=
ght of 100%, which is in some sense the =E2=80=9Cnormal=E2=80=9D risk weigh=
t.=C2=A0The crude rule of thumb =E2=80=94=C2=A0not particularly accurate, b=
ut a useful shorthand =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that banks need to have capital of =
8% of their risk-weighted assets. So a bank with $100 of corporate loans ne=
eds at least $8 of equity capital; it can borrow the other $92. A bank with=
 $100 of Bitcoin needs $100 of equity capital; it can=E2=80=99t use any dep=
osits at all to buy those Bitcoins.
These risk weights are set by regulation and are necessarily somewhat arbit=
rary; the regulators try to estimate the riskiness of various classes of th=
ings, and to assign higher risk weights to riskier things, but there=E2=80=
=99s only so much nuance they can manage. Some corporate loans are riskier =
than others, but will be lumped in with the same risk weight.
And so a big part of the bank=E2=80=99s financial engineering operation is =
optimizing risk-based capital. For instance: If a bank has $100 of stuff th=
at gets a 100% risk weight, and can somehow split it into $80 of stuff with=
 a 0% risk weight and $20 of stuff with a 300% risk weight, then that=E2=80=
=99s good, that=E2=80=99s what it wants, that reduces its risk-weighted ass=
ets from $100 to $60, which reduces its capital requirements, which increas=
es its ability to return money to shareholders. And this is the explanation=
 for  capital relief trades, and also in some loose sense the explanation f=
or  the 2008 financial crisis: If you slice your risky thing exactly right,=
 you will end up with a collection of new things that look less risky, to c=
apital regulators, than the original thing.=C2=A0
If you are a bank with a big tax equity financing business, a natural quest=
ion to ask is, well, how risky is this? Specifically:
=09Is it like a=C2=A0corporate loan, since it=E2=80=99s an investment in a =
series of predictable cash flows, at some agreed yield, from a business?=09=
Or is it like=C2=A0equity=C2=A0in a private company, since, technically, th=
at=E2=80=99s what it is?

There is no particularly correct answer to that; the answer is just =E2=80=
=9Cwhatever you can convince the capital regulators it is.=E2=80=9D But obv=
iously the answer that you=C2=A0want, as a bank, is that it=E2=80=99s a loa=
n. And in fact that seems to be the answer in US capital regulation: Tax eq=
uity financing normally  gets a 100% risk weight.=C2=A0In fact, the Office =
of the Comptroller of the Currency, which regulates banks, allows these dea=
ls=C2=A0=E2=80=9Conly if the transaction is the functional equivalent of a =
loan,=E2=80=9D and it does allow them: From the bank capital regulators=E2=
=80=99 perspective, tax equity financing is a loan.
That=E2=80=99s=C2=A0really=C2=A0how financial engineering works: You build =
a thing that looks like equity to the IRS (so the bank can get the tax cred=
it), but that looks like debt to the capital regulators (so it gets a lower=
 risk weight). You check the equity boxes for the IRS and the debt boxes fo=
r the OCC.=C2=A0You thread the needle so that it looks like different thing=
s to different regulators, looking like debt when debt is better and like e=
quity when equity is better.
But US capital regulators have launched a big revision of capital requireme=
nts, so the answer might change. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Natasha White and=
 Alastair Marsh report:

Senior Wall Street bankers are warning that a plan by US regulators to rewr=
ite the rules of tax-equity investing will deliver a major blow to a market=
 dominated by JPMorgan Chase & Co. and Bank of America Corp.
At issue is the perceived risk of tax-equity investments, which are a form =
of financing in which banks provide capital to green projects in exchange f=
or tax credits. It=E2=80=99s a market in which JPMorgan and BofA have been =
estimated to do more than 50% of the roughly $20 billion worth of annual tr=
ansactions.=C2=A0
Last July, the three agencies that decide bank capital requirements in the =
US (the Federal Reserve, Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and Office of the =
Comptroller of the Currency) unveiled what=E2=80=99s come to be known as th=
e Basel 3 Endgame. =E2=80=A6.
A part of that broader proposal is a requirement that banks quadruple the r=
isk weights they assign to tax-equity investments, forcing them to signific=
antly raise the amount of capital they set aside for renewable energy proje=
cts. ...
Law firm Clifford Chance has warned that the risk-weight proposal would mak=
e it =E2=80=9Cprohibitively expensive=E2=80=9D for banks to continue doing =
certain tax-equity investments, which is =E2=80=9Ccertain to have a harmful=
=E2=80=9D impact on green finance. ACORE, a trade group that represents ren=
ewable project developers, has said the plan threatens to =E2=80=9Cderail t=
he clean energy transition.=E2=80=9D

Here are=C2=A0the Clifford Chance memo=C2=A0and the  ACORE report. The poin=
t is that =E2=80=9Cnon-publicly traded equity exposures,=E2=80=9D like co-o=
wning a green energy joint venture, normally get a 400% risk weight. Tax eq=
uity financing somewhat accidentally got loopholed into the 100% risk-weigh=
t category before, but the new rules will close that loophole=C2=A0and it w=
ill get a 400% weight.
  [3]

Unless the banks complain loudly enough that the regulators hear them and p=
ut back a loophole for tax equity financing. And why not? None of this is r=
eal; none of it has any objective truth; tax equity financing isn=E2=80=99t=
 =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D equity or =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D debt. If you w=
ant more tax revenue, you make it harder to sell the tax credit; if you wan=
t more green energy=C2=A0financing, you make it easier to sell the tax cred=
it. If you want better capitalized banks, you raise the capital requirement=
s for tax equity financing; if you want more green energy financing, you lo=
wer the requirements. Banks obviously know what they want, and they enginee=
red a product to get it; now the question is what policymakers prefer.

