so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Basel endgame vs. green equity</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way that the US government encourages a lo=
t of green energy projects is by giving them tax credits. If you build a po=
wer plant that runs on certain sorts of renewable resources, the Internal R=
evenue Service will give you some money=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0call it 0.3 cen=
ts per killowatt-hour<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94 for generating that power, which you can use to reduce =
your taxes.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is a reasonably safe stream of cash flows=
. Not totally safe =E2=80=94=C2=A0your plant could burn down, prices could =
collapse or costs could rise so much that it is no longer economical to run=
 it, the tax code could change =E2=80=94=C2=A0but broadly speaking you can =
estimate how much power the plant will produce=C2=A0 per year and then mult=
iply that by 0.3 cents to get a fairly predictable=C2=A0annual tax credit.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Finance being what it is, if you are building =
a green energy project, you will probably sell that tax credit. If your pro=
ject will generate a quasi-guaranteed stream of cash flows of $X per year f=
or the next Y years, then you can compute the present value of those cash f=
lows=C2=A0and sell them, today, for that amount. This is good because you p=
robably need a lot of cash, today,=C2=A0to build the green energy project.=
=C2=A0The government wants to encourage you to build the project, but the g=
overnment doesn=E2=80=99t just hand you the money to do it. Instead the gov=
ernment promises to pay you $X per year if you succeed in building the proj=
ect, and you need to take that promise and exchange it for cash today in or=
der to actually build the project.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The person giving you the cash =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
the person paying you money up front today in exchange for a promise of the=
 future tax credit =E2=80=94=C2=A0is probably a big US bank, for a few reas=
ons. For one thing, banks are where the money is, and this sort of thing =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0providing financing today in exchange for a reasonably safe=
=C2=A0promise of future steady cash flows =E2=80=94=C2=A0is what banks do. =
And=C2=A0<em>financial engineering=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94 looking at a provisi=
on of the tax code and being like =E2=80=9Cyeah we can wring some profits o=
ut of that" =E2=80=94=C2=A0is also what banks do.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, in the 2020s, a big part of what banks d=
o is (1) promise to finance=C2=A0renewable energy projects and (2) deflect =
criticism for financing fossil-fuel projects. (And, in the US, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34162107.258396/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cudGV4YXN0cmlidW5lLm9yZy8yMDIyLzA4LzI0L3RleGFzLWJveWNvdHQtY29tcGFuaWVzLWZvc=
3NpbC1mdWVscy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc27b9334" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> vice versa</a>.)=
 So buying these tax credits =E2=80=94 paying=C2=A0the upfront costs of gre=
en energy projects in exchange for the future green-energy tax credits =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0is a good way for the banks to make money, do financial enginee=
ring, and show their shareholders and critics that they are financing green=
 energy projects.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have suggested that the banks are=C2=A0<em>b=
uying=C2=A0</em>the credits, and that the people building the projects =E2=
=80=94 the =E2=80=9Csponsors=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0are=C2=A0<em>selling=
=C2=A0</em>them, but that is not the correct terminology. You don=E2=80=99t=
 go around selling tax credits, and your tax lawyers will get mad if you sa=
y that. (Nothing here, of course, is tax advice.) The tax credit is not you=
r property; it is an artifact of US tax law. The only way for the bank to g=
et the tax credit is by qualifying for the tax credit, and <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34162107.258396/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYXNldG=
V4dC5jb20vY2FzZS9oaXN0b3JpYy1ib2FyZHdhbGstaGFsbC1sbGMtdi1jb21tci1vZi1pbnRlc=
m5hbC1yZXZlbnVl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB72e7a957" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the way to qual=
ify for the tax credit</a> is by=C2=A0<em>owning=C2=A0</em>the renewable en=
ergy project.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so the way this actually works is that the=
 renewable energy project is set up as some sort of partnership or limited =
liability company or joint venture, and the sponsor is a co-owner and the b=
ank is another co-owner. And the partnership agreement says that the sponso=
r gets most of the profits (and risk) from running the business and finding=
 customers and selling electricity at market rates and so forth, and the ba=
nk gets the tax credit. They are not=C2=A0<em>exactly=C2=A0</em>joint owner=
s, but they are joint owners=C2=A0<em>enough=C2=A0</em>for the bank to take=
 the tax credit. They have murmured the proper incantations to call themsel=
ves co-owners and take the tax credit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The IRS actually gives instructions on what so=
rts of incantations you have to say. The IRS is in sort of a weird position=
 here. On the one hand, it wants to prevent abusive tax shelters and genera=
lly uphold the aesthetic coherence of the tax code, so it does not want to =
allow people to just go around selling tax credits.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, the IRS=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0=
</em>want to encourage these projects to get built, which does, practically=
, requiring selling the tax credit. So it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/34162107.258396/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaXJzLmdvdi9wdWIvaXJ=
zLWRyb3AvcnAtMDctNjUucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB37565768" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> provi=
des</a>=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34162=
107.258396/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaXJzLmdvdi9wdWIvaXJzLWRyb3AvcnAtMTQtMTIucGRm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7b02c896" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">guidance</a>=C2=A0on, like, what is=
 the least you can do to qualify. The bank does need to take some risk, to =
share in the downside of the project; the sponsor can=E2=80=99t guarantee t=
he tax credits. But the usual way it works, according to the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34162107.258396/aHR0cHM6Ly9hY29y=
ZS5vcmcvcmVzb3VyY2VzL3RoZS1yaXNrLXByb2ZpbGUtb2YtcmVuZXdhYmxlLWVuZXJneS10YXg=
tZXF1aXR5LWludmVzdG1lbnRzLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB22173b05" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Ame=
rican Council on Renewable Energy</a>, is that the bank and the sponsor for=
m a project partnership, the bank =E2=80=9Cprovides between one-third to tw=
o-thirds of the total capital,=E2=80=9D and the bank gets back =E2=80=9C99%=
 of the tax attributes and a minority share of the cash, typically between =
5% and 30%,=E2=80=9D for a while. This ends either when the bank reaches it=
s target return (a =E2=80=9Cyield-based flip=E2=80=9D) or after an agreed a=
mount of time (a =E2=80=9Ctime-based flip=E2=80=9D), after which the bank=
=E2=80=99s share of the tax credit goes down (=E2=80=9Cusually to about 5%=
=E2=80=9D) and the sponsor can buy it out.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is called =E2=80=9Ctax equity financing,=
=E2=80=9D because for tax-law-incantation purposes, the bank is an=C2=A0<em=
>equity owner=C2=A0</em>of the partnership. But for practical purposes, peo=
ple kind of think of it as=C2=A0<em>debt=C2=A0</em>financing, because the b=
ank is=C2=A0providing upfront money in exchange for a reasonably certain, r=
easonably fixed, reasonably time-limited=C2=A0return. It does not really sh=
are in the upside and the downside of the project; it=E2=80=99s just puttin=
g up money to buy the tax credit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s how financial engineering works=
: You build a thing that looks like debt to the sponsor, and that looks lik=
e debt to the bank (so it=E2=80=99s happy to =E2=80=9Clend=E2=80=9D the mon=
ey), but that looks like equity to the IRS (so the bank can get the tax cre=
dit).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But nothing is that simple. Banks are doing a =
lot of financial engineering behind the scenes, too, particularly for their=
 capital requirements. A bank funds itself with a mix of cheap debt (deposi=
ts, etc.) and expensive capital (shareholder equity), and capital regulatio=
n determines how much capital it needs. The capital regulation is focused l=
argely on the=C2=A0<em>riskiness=C2=A0</em>of the bank=E2=80=99s assets: A =
bank that holds mostly Treasury bills needs very little capital, while a ba=
nk that holds mostly Bitcoin needs a ton. This is called =E2=80=9Crisk-base=
d capital,=E2=80=9D and it is expressed in terms of =E2=80=9Crisk weights=
=E2=80=9D: Treasury bills have a risk weight of 0%, because they are safe, =
while <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34162107.258=
396/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTA=
vbWF5YmUtZ2FtZXN0b3AtaXMtZ29vZC1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyOTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdX=
RtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMTI5JnV0b=
V9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB779e1ebc" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Bi=
tcoin has a risk weight of 1,250%</a>, because it is risky. Standard corpor=
ate loans usually have a risk weight of 100%, which is in some sense the =
=E2=80=9Cnormal=E2=80=9D risk weight.=C2=A0The crude rule of thumb =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0not particularly accurate, but a useful shorthand =E2=80=94=C2=A0i=
s that banks need to have capital of 8% of their risk-weighted assets. So a=
 bank with $100 of corporate loans needs at least $8 of equity capital; it =
can borrow the other $92. A bank with $100 of Bitcoin needs $100 of equity =
capital; it can=E2=80=99t use any deposits at all to buy those Bitcoins.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These risk weights are set by regulation and a=
re necessarily somewhat arbitrary; the regulators try to estimate the riski=
ness of various classes of things, and to assign higher risk weights to ris=
kier things, but there=E2=80=99s only so much nuance they can manage. Some =
corporate loans are riskier than others, but will be lumped in with the sam=
e risk weight.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so a big part of the bank=E2=80=99s financ=
ial engineering operation is optimizing risk-based capital. For instance: I=
f a bank has $100 of stuff that gets a 100% risk weight, and can somehow sp=
lit it into $80 of stuff with a 0% risk weight and $20 of stuff with a 300%=
 risk weight, then that=E2=80=99s good, that=E2=80=99s what it wants, that =
reduces its risk-weighted assets from $100 to $60, which reduces its capita=
l requirements, which increases its ability to return money to shareholders=
. And this is the explanation for <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/34162107.258396/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDUtMjUvZXVyb3BlYW4tYmFua3MtZ2V0LWNyZWF0aXZlLXdpdGgtY2FwaX=
RhbC1yZWxpZWY_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyOTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1d=
G1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMTI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0=
dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8c06884d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> capital relief trades</a>,=
 and also in some loose sense the explanation for <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34162107.258396/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucGVubnByZXN=
zLm9yZy85NzgwODEyMjQzNTc0L2VuZ2luZWVyaW5nLXRoZS1maW5hbmNpYWwtY3Jpc2lzLw/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0943ba9d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the 2008 financial crisis</a>: If =
you slice your risky thing exactly right, you will end up with a collection=
 of new things that look less risky, to capital regulators, than the origin=
al thing.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a bank with a big tax equity financ=
ing business, a natural question to ask is, well, how risky is this? Specif=
ically:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Is it like a=C2=A0<em>corporate loan<=
/em>, since it=E2=80=99s an investment in a series of predictable cash flow=
s, at some agreed yield, from a business?</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">Or is it like=C2=A0<em>equity=C2=A0in a private company</em>, since=
, technically, that=E2=80=99s what it is?</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is no particularly correct answer to tha=
t; the answer is just =E2=80=9Cwhatever you can convince the capital regula=
tors it is.=E2=80=9D But obviously the answer that you=C2=A0<em>want</em>, =
as a bank, is that it=E2=80=99s a loan. And in fact that seems to be the an=
swer in US capital regulation: Tax equity financing normally <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34162107.258396/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Y2xpZmZvcmRjaGFuY2UuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZGFtL2NsaWZmb3JkY2hhbmNlL2JyaWVmaW5ncy8=
yMDIzLzEwL0Jhc2VsJTIwSUlJJTIwRW5kZ2FtZSUyMFByb3Bvc2FsJTIwKElJKS5wZGY/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB3b79cf14" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> gets a 100% risk weight</a>.=C2=A0In =
fact, the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, which regulates banks,=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34162107.258396/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cub2NjLmdvdi9uZXdzLWlzc3VhbmNlcy9idWxsZXRpbnMvMjAyMS9idWxsZXRp=
bi0yMDIxLTE1Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBea1cbf78" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">allows these=
 deals</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=9Conly if the transaction is the functional equivale=
nt of a loan,=E2=80=9D and it does allow them: From the bank capital regula=
tors=E2=80=99 perspective, tax equity financing is a loan.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>really</em>=C2=A0how f=
inancial engineering works: You build a thing that looks like equity to the=
 IRS (so the bank can get the tax credit), but that looks like debt to the =
capital regulators (so it gets a lower risk weight). You check the equity b=
oxes for the IRS and the debt boxes for the OCC.=C2=A0You thread the needle=
 so that it looks like different things to different regulators, looking li=
ke debt when debt is better and like equity when equity is better.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But US capital regulators have launched a big =
revision of capital requirements, so the answer might change. Bloomberg=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34162=
107.258396/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEt=
Mjgvd2FsbC1zdHJlZXQtc2F5cy1iYXNlbC0zLWVuZGdhbWUtcHV0cy1ncmVlbi1pbnZlc3RtZW5=
