HVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaf318ddd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Natasha White and Alasta=
ir Marsh report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Senior Wall Street bankers are warning that a =
plan by US regulators to rewrite the rules of tax-equity investing will del=
iver a major blow to a market dominated by JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. and Ban=
k of America Corp.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At issue is the perceived risk of tax-equity i=
nvestments, which are a form of financing in which banks provide capital to=
 green projects in exchange for tax credits. It=E2=80=99s a market in which=
 JPMorgan and BofA have been estimated to do more than 50% of the roughly $=
20 billion worth of annual transactions.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last July, the three agencies that decide bank=
 capital requirements in the US (the Federal Reserve, Federal Deposit Insur=
ance Corp. and Office of the Comptroller of the Currency) unveiled what=E2=
=80=99s come to be known as the Basel 3 Endgame. =E2=80=A6.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A part of that broader proposal is a requireme=
nt that banks quadruple the risk weights they assign to tax-equity investme=
nts, forcing them to significantly raise the amount of capital they set asi=
de for renewable energy projects. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Law firm Clifford Chance has warned that the r=
isk-weight proposal would make it =E2=80=9Cprohibitively expensive=E2=80=9D=
 for banks to continue doing certain tax-equity investments, which is =E2=
=80=9Ccertain to have a harmful=E2=80=9D impact on green finance. ACORE, a =
trade group that represents renewable project developers, has said the plan=
 threatens to =E2=80=9Cderail the clean energy transition.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/34162107.258396/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2xpZmZvcmRjaGFuY2=
UuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZGFtL2NsaWZmb3JkY2hhbmNlL2JyaWVmaW5ncy8yMDIzLzEwL0Jhc2VsJ=
TIwSUlJJTIwRW5kZ2FtZSUyMFByb3Bvc2FsJTIwKElJKS5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
C3b79cf14" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">the Clifford Chance memo</a>=C2=A0and the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34162107.258396/aHR0cHM6Ly9hY29y=
ZS5vcmcvcmVzb3VyY2VzL3RoZS1yaXNrLXByb2ZpbGUtb2YtcmVuZXdhYmxlLWVuZXJneS10YXg=
tZXF1aXR5LWludmVzdG1lbnRzLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC22173b05" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> ACO=
RE report</a>. The point is that =E2=80=9Cnon-publicly traded equity exposu=
res,=E2=80=9D like co-owning a green energy joint venture, normally get a 4=
00% risk weight. Tax equity financing somewhat accidentally got loopholed i=
nto the 100% risk-weight category before, but the new rules will close that=
 loophole=C2=A0and it will get a 400% weight.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Unless the banks complain loudly enough that t=
he regulators hear them and put back a loophole for tax equity financing. A=
nd why not? None of this is real; none of it has any objective truth; tax e=
quity financing isn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D equity or =E2=80=9Cr=
eally=E2=80=9D debt. If you want more tax revenue, you make it harder to se=
ll the tax credit; if you want more green energy=C2=A0financing, you make i=
t easier to sell the tax credit. If you want better capitalized banks, you =
raise the capital requirements for tax equity financing; if you want more g=
reen energy financing, you lower the requirements. Banks obviously know wha=
t they want, and they engineered a product to get it; now the question is w=
hat policymakers prefer.</p>
